===========================================================================
MANDATORY HOUSE STYLE — PRESENT PERFECT TENSE
===========================================================================
Every regulatory action is reported using the PAST PARTICIPLE form of the
verb, combined with the auxiliary "has", "have", or "has/have been".
This is the house voice — deviation is treated as a style failure.

CORRECT (present perfect / past participle):
  - "The Water Regulation 2026 (Victoria) HAS BEEN MADE under the Water
     Act 1989 (Vic)."
  - "Melbourne Water HAS ANNOUNCED that ..."
  - "Sunwater HAS ADVISED that ..."
  - "Notices HAVE BEEN ISSUED in Government Gazette No. 18."
  - "The MDBA HAS MADE AVAILABLE its latest weekly water report."
  - "The Plan HAS COMMENCED on 15 April 2026."
  - "The Minister HAS PUBLISHED amendments to the scheme."

INCORRECT — do NOT use any of these voices:
  - Simple past:         "The Regulation WAS MADE ..."          (wrong)
  - Simple present:      "The Agency ANNOUNCES ..."             (wrong)
  - Present continuous:  "The Agency IS ANNOUNCING ..."         (wrong)
  - Future (unprompted): "The Plan WILL COMMENCE ..."           (wrong)

The only time the future tense is acceptable is when the source text
itself uses "will" to describe a dated future event (e.g. "the regulation
will take effect on 1 May 2026"). Even then, state the act of making /
announcing in present perfect: "The regulation HAS BEEN MADE and will
take effect on 1 May 2026."

Preferred auxiliary + participle combinations:
  has / have           + announced, advised, revised, updated, commenced,
                         introduced, consolidated, released
  has / have been      + made, issued, published, released, revised,
                         updated, introduced, gazetted

===========================================================================
HALLUCINATION RULES (NON-NEGOTIABLE — Stage 8 validates each rule)
===========================================================================
1. QUOTES — Any text enclosed in "[...]" MUST appear as a verbatim
   substring of ARTICLE TEXT or SUPPLEMENTARY CONTENT. Do not paraphrase,
   do not rewrite, do not correct typos, do not change punctuation.
   If the source says `streamlining licence applications`, write exactly
   `streamlining licence applications` inside the quotes — not
   `streamline licenses` or any variation.

2. DATES — Every date in the draft MUST appear verbatim in the source.
   Source form is authoritative. Do not reformat:
     source "15 April 2026" → draft "15 April 2026"   (not "15/04/2026")
     source "Apr 15, 2026"  → draft "Apr 15, 2026"    (not "15 April 2026")

3. AGENCY NAMES — Only use agency names that appear explicitly in the
   source. Never invent acronyms. If the source uses the full name once
   and the short name thereafter, mirror the source. Common agencies:
   Melbourne Water, Sydney Water, Sunwater, SA Water, WaterNSW, Hunter
   Water, Barwon Water, Yarra Valley Water, South East Water, Greater
   Western Water, Coliban Water, Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA),
   Bureau of Meteorology (BoM), DCCEEW, DEECA, EPA Victoria, EPA NSW,
   NRAR, IPART, Essential Services Commission.

4. ACTS / PLANS / INSTRUMENTS — Copy the title verbatim including year
   and jurisdiction suffix, e.g. "Water Act 1989 (Vic)",
   "Water Act 2000 (Qld)", "Water Management Act 2000 (NSW)",
   "Basin Plan 2012 (Cth)".

5. NO EDITORIAL LANGUAGE — Do not add adjectives of judgement that are
   absent from the source: "significant", "major", "long-awaited",
   "landmark", "controversial", "streamlined". If the source says so,
   quote it. If not, omit.

6. MISSING FACTS — If a slot cannot be filled from the source:
     - Optional slot (e.g. a second quote, a third bullet) → OMIT the
       slot and clean up its surrounding punctuation so the sentence
       still reads correctly.
     - Required slot (Title, Agency, Date) → write exactly
       `(not stated in source)` — Stage 8 detects this marker and
       routes the draft to editor review.

